I believe the issue is that the `{{explain_document}}` method is expecting a key that says `{{stages}}` or `{{serverPipeline}}` (with the `{{EXPLAIN}}` and `{{EXPLAIN_LEGACY}}` constants) but is not expecting the returned `{{splitPipeline}}` result.
  

The query structure is approximately:
{code:json}[
  {
    "$match"=>{
      "$or"=>[
        {
          "field_a"=>{
            "$in"=>[
              "field_a_1",
              "field_a_2"
            ]
          }
        }
      ],
      "field_b"=>{
        "$in"=>[
          "field_b_1",
          "field_b_2"
        ]
      },
      "field_i"=>{
        "$gte"=>Tue,
        09Jan201815: 33: 52-0800,
        "$lte"=>Wed,
        09Jan201915: 33: 52-0800
      },
      "$and"=>[
        {
          "field_c"=>{
            "$ne"=>true
          }
        },
        {
          "$or"=>[
            {
              "field_d"=>"field_d_1"
            },
            {
              "field_d"=>nil
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  }"$project"=>{
    "field_e"=>1,
    "field_b"=>1,
    "inbound"=>{
      "$cond"=>[
        {
          "$setIsSubset"=>[
            [
              "$f.f_a"
            ],
            [
              "f.fa_1",
              "f.fa_2"
            ]
          ]
        },
        false,
        true
      ]
    }
  },
  "$group"=>{
    "_id"=>{
      "field_b"=>"$field_b",
      "field_g"=>{
        "$field_g"=>{
          "$add"=>[
            "$e",
            -28800000
          ]
        }
      },
      "field_h"=>{
        "$field_h"=>{
          "$add"=>[
            "$field_e",
            -28800000
          ]
        }
      },
      "h"=>"$h"
    },
    "count"=>{
      "$sum"=>1
    }
  }
]
{code}

Using the aggregation pipeline with a match query with a `start_date` like this one
{code:java}
match_date = { '$match': { 'created_at': { '$gte': start_date } }{code}
It would seem that the offset is ignored when using ActiveSupport::TimeWithZone (astwz) objects that have an offset. 

Assume the server is in Paris/UTC+2 and
{code:java}
start_date_astwz = 1.hour.ago #=> Thu, 03 May 2018 09:52:46 CEST +02:00{code}
Then when using the match date, the time returnes would actually be 
{code:java}
Thu, 03 May 2018 09:52:46 CEST +00:00 (so 2 hours in the future){code}
 

When converting to Time (for instance using `.utc`) it works as expected, so I guess a fix would be to systematically call .utc
{code:java}
start_date_time = 1.hour.ago.utc #=> "2018-05-03T07:53:33.060Z" # and works fine{code}

Per the discussion in #drivers, retryable writes are specified to not be performed when in transaction context. retryable_writes_spec.rb has no mention of the word "transaction", and retryable_spec.rb has the following:

{code}
allow(session).to receive(:in_transaction?).and_return(false)
{code}

These tests need to be expanded to test that writes are not retried when transactions are used.

Neither modern nor legacy retryable writes should be performed when in a transaction.
